Nickel5 team - this is the very scammer. This is what he is talking about. We went through this with you in February, and now I am preparing an evidence base in addition to what is already in the 48th subnet and which const has become familiar with since today.

I don't know what this means.  If you're accusing the subnet owners of running a scam, you'll need to provide more objectively-verifiable info.  Make sure you check the #📌・rules .

I'd really appreciate it if people would stop laying down the accusations until the proof has already been published and established.  If you've made a technical case to const, then I'm sure he will post about it.  But simply saying "I've proven that so-and-so is a scammer" is not proof.
If it helps, I can time out people so you're not tempted to lay down accusations without the info being in place first.
Kat..stop be in auto-mode. We talked with const about that today. He gave me a green light to investigate and collect data about them.

i have a start point. but now it's time for much more work to collect data for really quality document.

For this reason, you will see me in several subnets with this topic, but not for the purpose of accusations - they will come later, but for the purpose of collecting data and questioning miners. The more hands and heads, the faster you will see all the data.

You're welcome to ask questions and express concerns, as long as you do it in a constructive and civil fashion (iaw the #📌・rules ).  Expressing a concern is fine and asking for information is also fine.  But don't accuse people of scamming or intentionally malicious behavior until you have objectively-verifiable proof that you can provide.  Thanks.

Yes, I know your position and I promise not to cross the line without reason. But sometimes it will just look like that because of language restrictions. I apologize in advance if that happens, a little patience, please, in the coming days.

@geardici | Nickel5  @qucat | Nickel5 @oneandahalfcats | Nickel5 lwhats going on? Can you please refer to the messages above?
I ask them the same question both publicly and personally, but they have been silent since July 11th. FYI

Hello @EnJoystick and @BittensorFans  can you please clarify the problem or pattern that you are "collecting data" on and why you're convinced there is a scammer involved?

If you have a concern about the weights or scoring, please feel free to share and I am happy to take a look and answer questions. As you are aware, our codebase is open source and you are free to run a validator to replicate results if you have concerns.

I'd appreciate that you not throw around baseless accusations - it sounds like a lot of your pain points have to do with weight copying/malicious validators, which is mostly out of our control besides the mechanisms we have in place to discourage them. This is an issue across many subnets

While I am collecting data for a full-fledged indictment, I can only give you a hint about what I know about the clippage exploit in the yuma consensus, which is so actively used by the group of people against whom I am investigating. More precisely, the investigation has long been completed, all that remains is to formalize it with evidence.

When you suggest simply running your validator code and reproducing the estimates, then you are either trying to lead me astray, or you really do not understand that the manipulation of weights is done not by the validator code provided by the subnet, but by its modification.

As for the offer to answer my questions - I have no questions for your team. I have answers, but they remain to be conveyed to the rest of the community in a convincing form.

I'd personally recommend starting with the evidence and then building a narrative.  Doing it the other way around isn't, imo, sound research.  But that's just my opinion (your mileage may vary, of course).

OK, I see what you are saying. I've just taken a look at the grafana link you've shared.

I would appreciate if you could be more clear about how you speak about this, because it initially sounded like you were accusing our team of manipulation. Now I see that you are focused on the Yuma validator, which is , as you know, not in our control.

I agree completely, that's why I don't give in.
In this case, they are again trying to get me to make premature accusations, so that later they can very easily answer "fiction, no evidence".

I agree completely, that's why I don't give in.
In this case, they are again trying to get me to make premature accusations, so that later they can very easily answer "fiction, no evidence".

Thanks Kat, for the gentle reminder, but I really do remember all the rules.

You really got the main point. It's not about personalities, it's about exploitation. But it just so happens that the same group of participants gathered around it.

I'm not fighting personalities, I want to eradicate the problem.

I dont think getting mad at subnet owners is the appropriate reaction here, nor do I think subnet channels are the appropriate place for this conversation. If you are noticing a pattern across several subnets, and it could be solved by chain level features or modifications - the right place to discuss would be in the dev discord server (church of rao)

As I am sure you're aware, the consensus is strong enough that any one validator manipulating weights should have relatively minimal impact on the final incentive outcome . On this subnet specifically, we have data syncing that means any drastic variations will be penalized by the consensus.

One thing I know for sure - bittensor is a constant adversarial environment, and exploits/manipulation are something that we deal with daily. I understand that it can be frustrating as a miner,  it's also frustrating as a dev. That said, please ensure that your frustration is directed to the appropriate place and appropriate people. If there's something I can do to help reduce the pattern you see on this specific subnet, please provide me with more data and I'd be happy to try and lock it down further with new features and/or adjustments to hyperparameters.

The exploit is that:
1) firstly, for effective manipulations there is no need for their strong amplitude. So to speak, "area" is enough. You know how weights work, so I think you will understand.
2) secondly, the Yuma consensus does not punish instantly and very harshly if someone falls out of it. You probably know that a certain "corridor" of deviation is allowed in it.
3) there is a third feature, but about it in due time.

I know about this place, but I'm not a programmer and I simply can't explain to them something they are more technically proficient in.
Besides, without collecting evidence of the need for such a level of change, it will be difficult and time-consuming to convince them.

Regarding the parameters that help fight this. I suggested Kappa to your colleague. He didn't have enough 2 months to figure out how it works. If you believe in your strengths, maybe you will succeed. In 48 I even gave a graph of how it works. In my opinion, it explains the essence quite transparently.

Yes, but those small manipulations are mostly outside of our control (unless we increase kappa hyperparam, which can mess up vtrust if we're too aggressive) . They also have a pretty minuscule effect in any one subnet. Across many subnets it may add up, but my original point still stands - there is absolutely no need to direct your anger towards us, nor is our subnet channel the appropriate place to talk about a greater pattern you may see.

If this is a network-wide issue, have you brought it up to Rhef in the Church of Rao yet?  Because he is *really intent* on fighting weight copiers and other forms of emissions manipulation.  I'm just saying.
(There's a built-in audience right there.)
And in that case, if you fix it for the *network*, you fix it for *everyone*.
kappa can be effective, but there are tradeoffs, because the data needs to be exactly in sync across all validators to maintain vtrust, which is difficult due to latency and other things
and yes, thanks Kat, I was just about to say that this all sounds like its something Rhef would be interested in chatting about

I spoke to one of its members (I don't want to ping, he's a terribly busy person in my opinion). "_Distributed_"... And I think he understands what I mean. But he sent me to write a commit on GitHub, and I'm not a programmer.
You don't need to write a commit, imo.  You can just add it as an Issue and provide as much detail as you can.
It would be in the "subtensor" repo, here: https://github.com/opentensor/subtensor/issues

I do this frequently, and I'm not a coder.  Mind you, it's mostly for docs.  But I did break the network that one time. (I kid.  I did not literally break the network.  I just suggested something that ended up resulting in an unintended chain panic down the line.)

Kappa is also a very flexible parameter, you can find a balance with synchronization in it, that's why it is not universal for everyone.

In addition, if there is competition (and admittedly tough) between miners, why can't there be one between validators for VTrust. I don't see any contradiction with White Paper.

I have experimented plenty with Kappa. It is not as flexible as you are suggesting, and the default value seems to be the most stable in my experience (and for the projects that I have worked on personally)

if you have a higher kappa, yes, WC/manipulation is penalized more heavily. But so are any inconsistencies due to data falling out of sync, network failures, etc. Honest validators shouldn't be penalized for inconsistencies that arise from distributed systems.

As a subnet dev, maintaining high vtrust is much more prioritized than preventing a minuscule manipulation that might result in a 1% difference in emission for a few miners.

if it was a 1% difference, I would never have even noticed it.
In the case of the 48th subnet, the exploit was used so aggressively that it determined which miners got 0% of the emission, and who got 80% of the emission. From the entire subnet.
This is very significant.
As you could see in that grafana link, the difference in weight between Yuma and other validators is 10-20%. That's enough to completely change your leaderboard. @geardici | Nickel5

Ok, well I dont work on that subnet, so I'm not sure what's going on there. But I deal with exploits practically every week, they are a huge pain in the ass. It's just sort of the nature of bittensor. And I always do my best to patch them as soon as i discover them , but sometimes it takes significant time to regain control over the subnet if there is a sybil attack or validators lose consensus.

Your claim that the 10-20% difference on a single validator is enough to change the leaderboard is definitely not true for sn30 , because the consensus is controlled by honest validators that sync with our database.

As long as your dashboard has miners sorted by emission and with such a distribution by Trust, you are wrong.

This is how I find subnets where this exploit being used.

Now open the graphana of any of these miners (whose Trust is significantly lower than their neighbors with similar emission) - and what do you think their weight will be from Yuma?

This approach works in 999 cases out of 1000.

Now you know that your leaderboard does not correspond to the fair one. And I will remind you once again, this is due to that exploit in the Yuma consensus and it is this that heals and should be healed with the help of Kappa.
(until, following your and Kat's advice, I explain in the Church of Rao how to close it. And for this I need convincing arguments that this needs to be done).

No, i'm not wrong. Yuma validator has 88k alpha stake weight and .59 vtrust.

Compared with the consensus stake weight across honest validators which is >1m alpha, their contribution to consensus is absolutely minuscule. I'm not going to bother doing the math, but it's probably less than 1% impact on final incentive.

if those miners with poorer trust are ranked, it is because the data they are generating still scores well enough across honest validators to achieve that rank. Lower trust doesn't necessarily indicate manipulation, it can also drop when there are inconsistencies in data syncing.

Well...
Then I'll go collect evidence anyway.
I even thought that you understood how everything works. But no, the same mistrust again.

You speak from the point of view of theory. I speak from the point of view of experience, since I lived under the conditions of what you call "insignificant influence".
It looks insignificant, but the nuance is that it is used successfully, since everyone considers it insignificant. And it looks quite unnoticeable.

Believe me, this is what has an incredible impact on the leaderboard in very competitive subnets (in terms of the quality of miners' results).

I went through this with my own miners. And by the way, I defeated it technically. But it is very expensive in terms of Tao. You have to give away about 30% of your income if you occupy the entire subnet to defeat the exploit.

And you have 0 chances if you occupy less than half of the subnet.

Now you can tell me lies, and I will continue my thankless job so that one day you will say "that man was right."

**"Lower trust doesn't necessarily indicate manipulation, it can also drop when there are inconsistencies in data syncing."**

That is, you named all the components, but for some reason did not connect one with the other.

I told you, open any of these drop-down miners on Grafana.
You will see what I am telling you.
It is this pattern that determines why, in your opinion, insignificant Yuma has such VTrust. But you explain this by the lack of synchronization and the quality of the product, while the weights of your subnet are uniquely horizontal (and have centralized sync with DB?)

Your argumentation is shocking. And at the same time it turned into the argumentation of the 48th subnet. Oh yeah, you are on the same team.

You're not even a miner on this subnet? I'll give you some credit - I think whatever pattern you are noticing may possibly be a case of subtle coordinated manipulation from WC validators across multiple subnets. I've seen it before in all shapes and forms and I dont doubt it still happens on most, if not all subnets.

As you know, bittensor is a (mostly) anonymous network and participants can act maliciously. I work very hard to ensure that the exploitation is kept to a minimum on the subnets I develop, and I am confident in the state of this subnet.

 The impact of a single validator with 88k staked is insignificant, because there is more than 1m stake across validators that we know are trustworthy.

I'm sorry that it has impacted your mining in other places, but this channel is for the discussion of mining on subnet 30, and your ramblings do not belong here. 

You're accusing me of lying (and perhaps acting maliciously) when it is clear you do not understand how consensus works, and you have failed to present any concrete evidence that would convince me there is a significant issue that needs to be addressed. If you were to present such evidence, I would be more than happy to act quickly on it. 

Consider our discussion concluded, please take your concerns elsewhere.

Pretty quickly you went from math and wanting to figure it out to the stage where I ask awkward questions and have no right to discuss anything about the subnet.

If I register a miner in your subnet right now, will I have the right to ask questions about its quality? Is that how you do things here?
good luck geardici 😂

Have you called in the cavalry? How's your subnet doing? Everything according to plan?

But it wasn't necessary to let it get to this state.

Oh , you have a right to discuss anything you want. I have a right to not engage with it further. I'll conclude with this.

Here's the (approximate) math for you.

Total stake weight of roughly 1.5M alpha across all validators.

~ 1.3M of that stake is held by honest, known validating teams that are running the open source code. (OTF, RT21, Rizzo, Kraken,and us)

you are concerned about a validator with 88k stake, and going as far as to infer we are colluding with them even though our weights look nothing like theirs.

this 88k represents approximately 5% of the total stake weight. The consensus algorithm is more complex than this, but for simplicity, just assume that this validator has about 5% of the total impact on final incentive. It's actually even less since they are not in consensus with other validators.

this, to me, is enough for me to very confidently say that their impact on final scores is indeed *insignificant*, and not enough to change the leaderboard. This is the consensus mechanism working as intended. Could it be better? sure - they're working on that. But that's out of my hands.

This concludes my contribution to this discussion, and my engagement with you. Please note that I will happily exercise my right to moderate this chat as I see fit, if you continue your rude behavior, baseless name calling, etc. I have no wish to engage with you further and I suggest that you direct your concerns to the appropriate channels and/or people.

have you just started? remember that there are tiers up to 45 day avg score. so even 10 days of perfect performance wont necessarily move you into the higher tiers, especially if odds are lower
as i understand it will take a certain amount of time for my key to level up, during that time i will need to maintain my key at a good performance to be able to reach a higher milestone

@geardici | Nickel5 I have one more question
It is possible to maintain good performance in a short time but in a long time it is very difficult, it is also impossible for someone to bet correctly for 30 days.
While just betting wrong 1 or 2 matches will cause the score to drop a lot and can lose the key.
I think we will need something for this problem otherwise it will be quite difficult for miners to maintain for a long time such as gradually reducing the score if wrong ...

well, because the time window increases as you move up tiers, it becomes slightly more forgiving to have a few days of bad performance.

The system is designed to identify and reward miners with consistently good long term performance that might translate to real world success. So its quite difficult and competitive, the top miners in this subnet likely use pretty sophisticated models to find good opportunities and execute.

This is about as fair as it gets, in my opinion. It's easy-ish to get into tier 2/3 with solid short term performance, but your strategy must have careful risk management in order to prove good long term performance and move into tiers 4/5, which are the tiers with the highest rewards
it's not a problem with the scoring system, its just that its very hard to secure the top slots

@geardici | Nickel5 I understand what you mean
But I see some of the top position keys they bet wrong quite a lot but their keys are still in very high position and get many rewards. You can take the current top 1 key as an example.
probably because they have made it to tier 5, which is more forgiving for bad days , because it takes a 45 day average performance.

I think it's unreasonable if after 45 days they are almost immortal. For example, the top 2 key can look at their editing history for 10 matches and get 8 wrong and only 2 correct, but they are still top 2. Do you think that's reasonable?
yes, because their average score is still high. they would be replaced by anyone who managed to get a better 45 day average

I understand but there is one problem recently the number of registrations is very large, many times after 3 days of immortality before the key points have been raised, it has already been lost. There are miners who own 30-40 keys and it is almost very difficult to maintain. Do you know this?

there is not much that we can do to prevent this kind of behavior. They still have to meet the minimum stake requirement and perform well in the short term, in order to leave tier 1, just like every other miner.

I think the problem is not that they want to get more rewards but they don't want other keys to climb or reach the milestone you said so they can maintain their top keys in the long term and maintain good rewards

The registration fee increased but it is still quite low and insignificant and they can totally make it up in 1 or 2 days. If the registration fee was higher I think this problem would be minimized and it would be more fair

I have noticed that things seem more competitive as a whole across many subnets. There are more mining groups/miners doing this kind of mass registration strategy. 
There is not a lot that we can do to combat this that we haven't already done, miners will need to adjust their own strategies to remain competitive against this behavior.

Hey guys, apologies for the radio silence. We've been busy with some other things and are shaping some big plans for the future of this subnet. I can't say much now until the plan is more developed, but it will remain in the sports category and likely be pretty similar in a lot of ways.

For any ongoing concerns, we'll take a look and try to address them with simple fixes for now. Please recall that if there is a match result that doesn't look right, you can submit a data dispute on bettensor.com and our team will review it. This is the easiest way to get results changed quickly.


As for the immunity period/mass registration discussion - We previously spent a long time on fine tuning this and we believe we've arrived at a pretty balanced place. 
Making immunity longer makes it **easier to mass register and kick decent performing miners out.

The tier system is the best way to handle this and keep all churn locked in the bottom percentile of miners. It is difficult to rise into higher tiers as it requires a strategy adjustment over time , but this is the best way to keep the reward for mass registration to a minimal amount
